  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very relaxed, let your body wake up. No pressure to hit pace yet.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Conversational effort throughout. If you can't hold a sentence, slow down. This is aerobic base work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace, let your heart rate settle naturally.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes of very easy jogging — no watch-watching, just feel.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Last 5 minutes at a gentle stroll-jog. Follow with calf and Achilles stretching given your history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday's easy run sets the tone for the week. At VDOT 46.7, your aerobic system is well-developed — these easy runs are where you consolidate that fitness, not where you prove it. Keep effort genuinely easy: 5:22–5:56/km is your range, and landing closer to 5:39–5:56 on a Monday is perfectly right. Given your Achilles history, a brief post-run calf raise routine (slow eccentrics) is worth keeping as a habit even in maintenance.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":11,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":251,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog for approximately 2 km. Include 4–6 strides of 20 seconds at interval effort in the final 2 minutes to prime your neuromuscular system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":25,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":251,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 1 km at 4:11/km (251 sec/km). This is controlled hard — not a sprint. You should feel like you could do one more rep at the end of the set, but wouldn't want to.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"400m jog recovery between each rep (~2 min). Keep moving — don't stop. This is active recovery.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy 1.5 km jog to flush the legs. No rushing — let your breathing fully recover.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog followed by dynamic drills: leg swings, high knees, and 4 x 20-second pickups building to interval pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Minimum 1.5 km easy jog. Follow with gentle hamstring and hip flexor stretching. Prioritize Achilles and calf mobility.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Tuesday intervals are the sharpest stimulus of the week. The 5 x 1 km structure at 4:11/km targets your VO2max — the ceiling of your aerobic engine. In a maintenance block, the goal isn't to push this ceiling higher, it's to keep it from drifting down. Five reps is the right volume: enough stimulus, not so much that recovery bleeds into the rest of the week. Your recent session of 5 x 1 km tells me this structure suits you well — trust that familiarity.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Recovery Easy Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":356,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"True recovery pace — the slow end of your easy range or slower. If your legs feel heavy from Tuesday, that's normal and expected. Honor it.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — the first 5 minutes of the run IS the warmup at this pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes after finishing. Gentle calf stretches and Achilles tendon mobility work.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday exists to promote recovery from Tuesday's intervals, not to add fitness. Running at the slow end of your easy range (5:56/km or even a touch slower) on days like this is a sign of training intelligence, not weakness. The physiological adaptation from Tuesday happens during this recovery window — so protecting it protects your gains. Six kilometers is intentionally short. Resist the urge to extend it.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Tempo Run\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":54,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog. Finish with 2–3 x 30-second pickups building toward threshold pace to prime your lactate system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"8 km continuous at 4:28/km (268 sec/km). Comfortably hard — you can speak in short phrases but not hold a conversation. This is your lactate threshold pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog to clear lactate and bring your system down gently.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog with gradual pace build. Include a few 30-second accelerations toward threshold pace in the final minute of the warmup.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 km easy jog minimum. Do not skip this — it accelerates lactate clearance and reduces next-day soreness. Calf and Achilles stretching after.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Thursday's tempo run is the backbone of your maintenance week. Eight kilometers at threshold pace (4:28/km) keeps your lactate threshold sharp — the single most important predictor of marathon performance. This mirrors your recent training session almost exactly, which is intentional: in maintenance, consistency and repeatability matter more than novelty. The effort should feel 'comfortably hard' — controlled, not labored. If you find yourself working harder than that to hold pace, back off 5–10 seconds per km rather than grinding.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady easy effort. Mid-range of your easy pace band. This is a buffer day between Thursday's tempo and Sunday's long run.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"First 5 minutes very easy — let Thursday's effort fully clear before settling into pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Easy walk or slow jog for 3 minutes. Calf raises and Achilles stretching as part of your routine.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday's easy run serves two purposes: it keeps your weekly volume consistent and it acts as a gentle flush after Thursday's threshold work. Eight kilometers at a comfortable 5:22–5:39/km is exactly right here. This is also a good day to run by feel — if you're feeling fresh, stay in the middle of the easy range. If Thursday's tempo left its mark, drift toward the slower end. Both are correct responses.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"title\":\"Active Recovery or Rest\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":0,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":0,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":0,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Optional: 30–40 minutes of low-impact cross-training — cycling, swimming, yoga, or mobility work. If your body is asking for full rest, honor that. Both are valid choices.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No structured warmup needed. If doing yoga or mobility, move gently into it.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5–10 minutes of gentle stretching, prioritizing calves, Achilles, hip flexors, and hamstrings.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your buffer before Sunday's long run. At six days per week of running, a cross-training or full rest day here is genuinely protective — it means you arrive at Sunday's long run with fresh legs rather than accumulated fatigue. Think of this as an investment in Sunday's quality, not a gap in your training. Light yoga, a gentle bike ride, or a swim are all excellent options. Full rest is equally valid. You know your body — trust that read.\",\"perceived_effort\":2},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":118,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":339,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 10 minutes very easy — slower than easy pace if needed. Let your body find its rhythm before settling in.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":98,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady aerobic effort at 5:56/km — the slow end of your easy range. This is not a race simulation. The goal is time on feet and aerobic stimulus, not pace. If conditions are warm, adjust pace accordingly — your Chicago Marathon experience is a good reminder of how heat affects effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":380,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 10 minutes at a very easy shuffle. Let your heart rate drift down naturally.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start slower than you think you need to. The first kilometer should feel almost too easy. This protects the quality of the final third of the run, which is where the real aerobic adaptation happens.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes after finishing. Prioritize rehydration and a carbohydrate-protein snack within 30 minutes. Gentle full-body stretching, with extra attention to calves and Achilles.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Sunday's long run is the anchor of your maintenance week. At 20 km and approximately 118 minutes, it sits right at your established long run distance — no increase needed in a maintenance block. The pace target of 5:56/km (the slow end of your easy range) is deliberate: long runs derive their value from duration and aerobic stimulus, not speed. Running them too fast is one of the most common training errors at your level, and it compromises recovery for the rest of the week. Your recent 21 km at 5:56/km shows you've got this dialed in well. One practical note: given your Achilles history, pay attention to how the tendon feels in the first 3–4 km. If there's any unusual tightness or discomfort beyond normal morning stiffness, it's worth shortening the run and checking in with a physio rather than pushing through. Your long-term consistency is worth protecting.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
